## No long ternaries

This is one of the most important rules in the codebase.

### ✗ Never — ternary with JSX blocks
```tsx
return (
  <View>
    {isVoice ? (
      <View style={styles.voiceContainer}>
        <PlayButton onPress={handlePlay} />
        <Waveform bars={waveBars} />
        <Text style={styles.duration}>{duration}</Text>
        <TranscribeButton onPress={handleTranscribe} />
      </View>
    ) : (
      <View style={styles.textContainer}>
        <Text style={styles.messageText}>{content}</Text>
      </View>
    )}
  </View>
)
```

### ✓ Always — extract components, ternary only picks between them
```tsx
return (
  <View>
    {isVoice ? <VoiceContent /> : <TextContent />}
  </View>
)
```

### The threshold: 2 lines of JSX inside a ternary → extract a component

```tsx
// ✓ Ternary is fine for single values
<Text style={isRead ? styles.read : styles.unread}>{text}</Text>

// ✓ Ternary is fine for single components
{isLoading ? <Spinner /> : <MessageList messages={messages} />}

// ✗ Ternary is not fine for blocks of JSX
{isLoading ? (
  <View>
    <Spinner />
    <Text>Loading...</Text>
  </View>
) : (
  <MessageList messages={messages} />
)}

// ✓ Extract it
{isLoading ? <LoadingState /> : <MessageList messages={messages} />}
```

### Early returns over ternaries for loading/error states
```tsx
// ✓ Good
if (isLoading) return <LoadingState />
if (error) return <ErrorState error={error} />
if (!messages.length) return <EmptyState />

return <MessageList messages={messages} />

// ✗ Bad
return isLoading ? <LoadingState /> : error ? <ErrorState /> : !messages.length ? <EmptyState /> : <MessageList />
```

