## Scalability — built for 10,000 concurrent users from day one

We do not build for a few people. We build for scale and fix it down to small
if we need to. The cost of retrofitting scale is 10x the cost of building it in.

10,000 concurrent users means:
- Thousands of simultaneous SSE connections
- Hundreds of BullMQ jobs in flight at any moment
- Database queries that must be fast under load
- No operations that block the event loop
- No shared in-memory state between instances

### Never block the event loop

Node.js is single-threaded. Anything that blocks it blocks every user.

```typescript
// ✗ Synchronous operations that block
const data = fs.readFileSync('file.txt')
const result = JSON.parse(largeJson) // fine for small, block for large

// ✓ Always async
const data = await fs.promises.readFile('file.txt')
```

Heavy CPU work (large JSON parsing, image processing) goes to a worker thread or
a separate service — never in the request path.

### Database — indexes on everything you query by

Every foreign key, every field in a WHERE clause, every ORDER BY field needs an index.
Un-indexed queries kill at scale.

```typescript
// schema/messages.schema.ts
export const messages = pgTable('messages', {
  id: uuid('id').primaryKey().defaultRandom(),
  userId: uuid('user_id').notNull().references(() => users.id),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow().notNull(),
  intent: text('intent'),
  kind: text('kind').notNull(),
}, (table) => ({
  // Index every field you filter or sort by
  userIdIdx: index('messages_user_id_idx').on(table.userId),
  createdAtIdx: index('messages_created_at_idx').on(table.createdAt),
  userCreatedIdx: index('messages_user_created_idx').on(table.userId, table.createdAt),
}))
```

### Database — always paginate, never return unbounded results

```typescript
// ✗ Returns entire history — breaks at scale
const messages = await db.select().from(messages).where(eq(messages.userId, userId))

// ✓ Always paginate
const MESSAGES_PER_PAGE = 50

const messages = await db
  .select()
  .from(messagesTable)
  .where(and(
    eq(messagesTable.userId, userId),
    before ? lt(messagesTable.createdAt, before) : undefined,
  ))
  .orderBy(desc(messagesTable.createdAt))
  .limit(MESSAGES_PER_PAGE)
```

### Database — use connection pooling

Never open a new DB connection per request.
Use a connection pool (Neon handles this for serverless, PgBouncer for dedicated).

```typescript
// drizzle config — pool size tuned to your compute
const pool = new Pool({
  connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL,
  max: 20,              // max connections in pool
  idleTimeoutMillis: 30000,
  connectionTimeoutMillis: 2000,
})
```

### Database — select only what you need

```typescript
// ✗ Selects entire row including embeddings and large fields
const messages = await db.select().from(messagesTable).where(...)

// ✓ Select only what the caller needs
const messages = await db
  .select({
    id: messagesTable.id,
    role: messagesTable.role,
    kind: messagesTable.kind,
    content: messagesTable.content,
    createdAt: messagesTable.createdAt,
  })
  .from(messagesTable)
  .where(...)
```

### SSE — one connection per user, managed carefully

10,000 concurrent users = 10,000 open SSE connections.
Each connection holds memory and a file descriptor.

```typescript
// SSE connections must be cleaned up on disconnect
export class SseService {
  private readonly connections = new Map<string, Response>()

  addConnection(userId: string, res: Response) {
    // Close any existing connection for this user first
    this.closeConnection(userId)
    this.connections.set(userId, res)

    // Clean up when client disconnects
    res.on('close', () => {
      this.connections.delete(userId)
    })
  }

  closeConnection(userId: string) {
    const existing = this.connections.get(userId)
    if (existing) {
      existing.end()
      this.connections.delete(userId)
    }
  }
}
```

In production with multiple instances, SSE connections need Redis pub/sub so
any instance can push to any user. See **`pem-backend.mdc`** / chat SSE architecture.

### BullMQ — configure concurrency intentionally

```typescript
// ✓ Set concurrency based on the job's resource cost
const worker = new Worker('embed-messages', embedProcessor, {
  connection: redis,
  concurrency: 20,   // cheap jobs — high concurrency
})

const agentWorker = new Worker('process-dump', agentProcessor, {
  connection: redis,
  concurrency: 5,    // expensive AI calls — lower concurrency to control cost
})
```

### BullMQ — always handle failure with retry and backoff

```typescript
// ✓ Every job configured with retry
await queue.add('embed-message', payload, {
  attempts: 3,
  backoff: {
    type: 'exponential',
    delay: 2000,        // 2s, 4s, 8s
  },
  removeOnComplete: { count: 100 },  // don't accumulate completed jobs
  removeOnFail: { count: 500 },
})
```

### Caching — cache what doesn't change per request

```typescript
// Task counts for the pill — expensive to compute, cache aggressively
const TASK_COUNTS_TTL_SECONDS = 60

async getTaskCounts(userId: string): Promise<TaskCounts> {
  const cacheKey = `task_counts:${userId}`
  const cached = await this.redis.get(cacheKey)
  if (cached) return JSON.parse(cached)

  const counts = await this.computeTaskCounts(userId)
  await this.redis.set(cacheKey, JSON.stringify(counts), 'EX', TASK_COUNTS_TTL_SECONDS)
  return counts
}

// Invalidate cache when tasks change
async markTaskDone(taskId: string, userId: string): Promise<void> {
  await this.db.update(...)
  await this.redis.del(`task_counts:${userId}`) // ← invalidate
}
```

### AI calls — never in the request path if they're slow

Classification (gpt-4o-mini, ~300ms) can be in the request path.
Agent responses (gpt-4o, 3-30 seconds) must be in BullMQ jobs.

```typescript
// ✓ Fast classification — OK in request path
@Post('messages')
async sendMessage(@Body() dto: SendMessageDto, @GetUser() user: AuthUser) {
  const message = await this.chatService.save(dto, user.id)
  const intent = await this.classifyIntent(dto.content) // ~300ms, acceptable
  await this.queue.add('process-message', { messageId: message.id, intent })
  return { messageId: message.id, status: 'received' }
}

// ✓ Slow agent — always in a job
// processMessage.job.ts
async process(job: Job) {
  const response = await runAgent(job.data) // can take 10-30 seconds
  await this.sse.push(job.data.userId, { event: 'pem_message', data: response })
}
```

### Observability — you cannot scale what you cannot see

Every service must emit structured logs, metrics, and traces.
If something breaks at 10,000 users you need to know where and why in seconds.

```typescript
// ✓ Structured logs — not console.log strings
this.logger.log({
  event: 'message.processed',
  messageId,
  userId,
  intent,
  durationMs: Date.now() - startTime,
  tokensUsed: result.usage.totalTokens,
})

// ✓ Log slow operations
const start = Date.now()
const result = await this.runAgent(payload)
const duration = Date.now() - start

if (duration > 10000) {
  this.logger.warn({
    event: 'agent.slow',
    messageId: payload.messageId,
    durationMs: duration,
  })
}
```

Track these metrics at minimum:
- Request latency (p50, p95, p99) per endpoint
- BullMQ job queue depth and processing time
- AI API latency and token usage per call
- SSE connection count
- DB query latency
- Error rate per endpoint

### Horizontal scaling — stateless services

NestJS instances must be stateless. No in-memory state that can't
exist on multiple instances simultaneously.

```typescript
// ✗ In-memory state — breaks with multiple instances
const activeSessions = new Map<string, Session>() // only exists on this instance

// ✓ State in Redis — shared across all instances
const session = await this.redis.get(`session:${userId}`)
```

### Scalability checklist — run through this for every new feature

- [ ] Does every DB query have indexes on all WHERE and ORDER BY fields?
- [ ] Is all data paginated — no unbounded queries?
- [ ] Are slow AI calls (gpt-4o) in BullMQ jobs, not the request path?
- [ ] Is the service stateless — no in-memory state shared between requests?
- [ ] Is the new endpoint rate-limited?
- [ ] Are there structured logs with timing for slow path operations?
- [ ] Is anything cacheable in Redis with appropriate TTL and invalidation?
- [ ] Are BullMQ jobs configured with retry and backoff?
- [ ] Does the SSE handler clean up connections on disconnect?

